 introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Brochwel ap Bledrus was born about 1004, in Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom. She married Brochwel ap Bledrus about 1026, in Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. She died about 1104, in Wales, United Kingdom, at the age of 102, and was buried in Wales, United Kingdom."},"et":{"ABT 1004–Abt 1104":"umbes 1004–umbes 1104","1000–1100":"1000–1100","1030–Male":"1030–Surnud","1040–Female":"1040–Surnud","1004–1104":"1004–1104","about 1030":"umbes 1030","1104":"1104","1004":"1004","Abt 1100":"umbes 1100","1100":"1100","ABT 1004":"umbes 1004","ABT 1026":"umbes 1026","1000":"1000","Abt 1104":"umbes 1104","1030":"1030","1040":"1040","Burton, Denbighshire, Wales":"Burton, Denbighshire, Wales","of Mon (Anglesey),Wales":"Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","Anglesey, Gwynedd, Wales":"Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom","Anglesey, Wales